{{Wiktionary|metapsychology}}
'''Metapsychology''' ([[Greek language|Greek]]: ''meta'' 'beyond, transcending', and ''ψυχολογία'' '[[psychology]]')<ref name=OMD>[https://archive.is/20070813174048/http://cancerweb.ncl.ac.uk/cgi-bin/omd?metapsychology Metapsychology Online Medical Dictionary]</ref> is that aspect of any psychological theory which refers to the structure of the theory itself (hence the prefix "meta") rather than to the entity it describes. The psychology is about the psyche; the metapsychology is about the psychology. The term is used mostly in discourse about psychoanalysis, the psychology developed by [[Sigmund Freud]], which today is regarded as a branch of science (with roots in the work of Freud's scientific mentors and predecessors, especially Helmholtz, Brucke, Charcot, and Janet) and/or a hermeneutics of understanding (with roots in Freud's literary sources, especially Sophocles and, to a lesser extent, Goethe and Shakespeare).  Emphasis on the scientific status of psychoanalysis has been renewed in the emerging discipline of neuropsychoanalysis, whose major exemplar is Mark Solms. The hermeneutic vision of psychoanalysis is the focus of influential works by Donna Orange.

==Freud and the ''als ob'' problem==
{{also|The Philosophy of 'As if'#Reception}}
[[Psychoanalytic]] metapsychology is concerned with the fundamental structure and concepts [[Freudian theory]].<ref name="OMD"/> [[Sigmund Freud]] first used the term on 13 February 1896 in a letter to [[Wilhelm Fliess]],<ref name="Routledge">{{cite book |last=Erwin |first=Edward |chapter= Metapsychology (p. 337) |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/?id=rX2w6QELtKgC&pg=PA337&dq=%22Freud's+first+recorded+use+of+the+word+%22metapsychology%22+is+in+a+letter+to+Fliess+(of+February+13,+1896)%22 |editor-last=Erwin |editor-first=Edward |title=The Freud encyclopedia. Theory, therapy, and culture |url=https://books.google.com/?id=rX2w6QELtKgC&printsec=frontcover |year=2002 |publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]] |location=New York City |isbn=978-0-415-93677-4}}</ref> to refer to his addition of [[Unconscious mind|unconscious]] processes to the conscious ones of traditional psychology. On March 10, 1898, he wrote to Fiess: "It seems to me that ({{lang-de|als ob}})<ref>{{de icon}} {{cite book |last=Roudinesco |first=Élisabeth |authorlink=Élisabeth Roudinesco |last2=Plon |first2=Michel |title=Wörterbuch der Psychoanalyse. Namen, Länder, Werke, Begriffe |url=https://books.google.com/?id=t1jyBQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |year=2013 |origyear=[https://books.google.com/?id=56-46LwawREC 2004] |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer-Verlag]] |location=[[Vienna]] |isbn=978-3-709-10640-2 |page=[https://books.google.com/?id=t1jyBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA679&dq=%22In+seinem+Brief+vom+10.+März+1898+an+Fließ%22%22als+ob%22 679]}}</ref> the theory of wish fulfillment has brought only the psychological solution and not the biological - or, rather, metapsychical - one. (I am going to ask you seriously, by the way, whether I may use the name metapsychology for my psychology that leads behind consciousness)."<ref>{{cite book |last=Reeder |first=Jurgen |title=Reflecting Psychoanalysis. Narrative and Resolve in the Psychoanalytic Experience |url=https://books.google.com/?id=38_kz3n4bbEC&printsec=frontcover |year=2002 |publisher=Karnac Books |location=London |isbn=9781780497105 |page=[https://books.google.com/?id=38_kz3n4bbEC&pg=PA10&dq=%22It+seems+to+me+that+the+theory+of+wish+fulfillment+has+brought+only+the+psychological+solution+and+not+the+biological+-+or,+rather,+metapsychical+-+one.+(I+am+going+to+ask+you+seriously,+by+the+way,+whether+I+may+use+the+name+metapsychology+for+my+psychology+that+leads+behind+consciousness)%22 10]}}</ref> Three years after completing his unpublished ''Project for a Scientific Psychology'', Freud's optimism had completely vanished. In a letter dated March 10 of that year he told Fliess: "I am not at all in disagreement with you, not at all inclined to leave psychology hanging in the air without an organic basis. But apart from this conviction, I do not know how to go on, neither theoretically nor therapeutically, and therefore must behave as if [''als läge'']<ref>{{de icon}} {{cite book |last=Spehlmann |first=Rainer |title=Sigmund Freuds Neurologische Schriften. Eine Untersuchung zur Vorgeschichte der Psychoanalyse |url=https://books.google.com/?id=v0ObBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |year=2013 |origyear=[https://books.google.com/?id=-ybmRgAACAAJ 1953] |publisher=Springer-Verlag |location=Vienna |isbn=978-3-642-47345-6 |page=[https://books.google.com/?id=v0ObBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA71&dq=Freud+%22Er+sagt+in+einem+Brief+vom+22.+9.+1898%22+%22als+läge%22 71]}}</ref> only the psychological were under consideration. Why I cannot fit it together [the organic and the psychological] I have not even begun to fathom".<ref>{{cite book |last=Freeman |first=Walter J. |authorlink=Walter Jackson Freeman III |editor-last1=Wang |editor-first1=Rubin |editor-last2=Gu |editor-first2=Fanji |editor-last3=Shen |editor-first3=Enhua |title=Advances in Cognitive Neurodynamics. Proceedings of the International Conference on Cognitive Neurodynamics - 2007 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Y-FwBPbpnZEC&printsec=frontcover |year=2008 |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer Science & Business Media]] |isbn=978-1-402-08387-7 |page=[https://books.google.com/?id=Y-FwBPbpnZEC&pg=PA366&dq=%22I+am+not+at+all+in+disagreement+with+you,+not+at+all+inclined+to+leave+psychology+hanging+in+the+air+without+an+organic+basis.+But+apart+from+this+conviction,+I+do+not+know+how+to+go+on,+neither+theoretically+nor+therapeutically,+and+therefore+must+behave+as+if+only+the+psychological+were+under+consideration.+Why+I+cannot+fit+it+together+%5Bthe+organic+and+the+psychological%5D+Ihave+not+even+begun+to+fathom%22 366]}}</ref> "When, in his 'Autobiographical Study' of 1925, Freud called his metapsychology a 'speculative superstructure'...the elements of which could be abandoned or changed once proven inadequate, he was, in the terminology of [[Immanuel Kant|Kant]]'s ''[[Critique of Judgment]]'',<ref>{{cite book |last=Cutrofello |first=Andrew |title=Imagining Otherwise. Metapsychology and the Analytic a Posteriori |url=https://books.google.com/?id=QDUy8xMXSrMC&printsec=frontcover |year=1997 |publisher=[[Northwestern University Press]] |location=[[Evanston, Illinois]] |isbn=978-0-810-11400-5 |page=[https://books.google.com/?id=QDUy8xMXSrMC&pg=PA105&dq=%22Kant's+famous%22%22as+if+(als+ob)+formula+concerning+the+idea+of+God%22%22The+ideal+of+the+supreme+being+is+nothing+but+a+regulative+principle+of+reason,+which+directs+us+to+look+upon+all+connection+in+the+world+as+if+it+originated+from+an+all-sufficient+necessary+cause%22 105]}}</ref> proposing a psychology ''als ob'' or ''as if'' – a [[heuristic]] model of mental functioning that did not necessarily correspond with external reality."<ref>{{cite book |editor-last1=Nicholls |editor-first1=Angus |editor-last2=Liebscher |editor-first2=Martin |title=Thinking the Unconscious. Nineteenth-Century German Thought |url=https://books.google.com/?id=MCJzE-SxDUgC&printsec=frontcover |year=2010 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |isbn=978-1-139-48967-6 |page=[https://books.google.com/?id=MCJzE-SxDUgC&pg=PA103&dq=%22When,+in+his+“Autobiographical+Study”+of+1925,+Freud+called+his+metapsychology+a+“speculative+superstructure”%22%22he+was,+in+the+terminology+of+Kant's+Critique+of+Judgment,+proposing+a+psychology+als+ob+or+as+if%22 103]}}</ref>

A salient example of Freud's own metapsychology is his chracterization of psychoanalysis as a "simultaneously closed system, fundamentally unrelated and impervious to the external world and as an open system inherently connected and responsive to environmental influence''.<ref name="ReferenceC">{{cite journal |last=Dunn |first=Jonathan |title=The foundational wisdom in Freud's and Loewald's metapsychologies |journal=Modern Psychoanalysis |date=2009 |volume=34 |issue=1 |pages=2–25 |publisher=Center for Modern Psychoanalytic Studies |url=https://search.proquest.com/openview/6559b62f61964d350d95da9f488c482a/1?pq-origsite=gscholar&cbl=36244}}</ref>

In the 1910s, Freud wrote a series of twelve essays, to be collected as ''Preliminaries to a Metapsychology''. Five of these were published independently under the titles: "Instincts and Their Vicissitudes," "Repression," "The Unconscious," "A Metapsychological Supplement to the Theory of Dreams," and "Mourning and Melancholia." The remaining seven remained unpublished, an expression of Freud's ambivalence about his own attempts to articulate the whole of his vision of psychoanalysis.  In 1919 he wrote to [[Lou Andreas-Salome]], "Where is my Metapsychology? In the first place it remains unwritten".<ref>{{cite book |last=Freud |first=Sigmund |authorlink=Sigmund Freud |title=On metapsychology: the theory of psychoanalysis |page=102 |publisher=The Penguin Freud Library |volume=11 |location=London |year=1991 |isbn=978-0-140-13801-6}}</ref> In 1920 he published ''[[Beyond the Pleasure Principle]]'', a text with metaphysical ambitions. 

Midcentury psychoanalyst [[David Rapaport]]<ref name="Erwin">Erwin, Edward (2002). [https://books.google.com/?id=rX2w6QELtKgC&pg=PA339&dq=Rapaport+%22Books+on+psychoanalysis+usually+deal+with+its+clinical+theory...+there+exists,+however,+a+fragmentary--yet+consistent--general+theory+of+psychoanalysis,+which+comprises+the+premises+of+the+special+(clinical)+theory,+the+concepts+built+on+it,+and+the+generalizations+derived+from+it...+named+metapsychology.%22 "Metapsychology (p. 339)"].</ref> defined the term thus: "Books on psychoanalysis usually deal with its clinical theory... there exists, however, a fragmentary—yet consistent—general theory of psychoanalysis, which comprises the premises of the special (clinical) theory, the concepts built on it, and the generalizations derived from it... named ''metapsychology''."<ref name = "Erwin"/>

